<td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>Had an interesting experience recently, involving my main char as a tanking cleric. Understand that i do not consider myself a tank, in most situations. However, here's what happened: <br /> <br />We started a North Ro normal LDON, with the following group: 65 cleric, 65 warrior, 58 warrior, 61 shammy, 65 wizard, 65 druid. <br /> <br />About 20 minutes in, the 58 warrior had to leave. No biggy, or so it seemed. <br /> <br />About 50 minutes in, with 18 out of 26 collected, the 65 warrior had a RL emergency, and had to go. <br /> <br />Hmm, that left: Wizard, druid, lower level shammy, and Cleric. <br /> <br />Well, not being one to give up, I said lets try it with me tanking. We had 40 minutes, and needed 8 collect to win (drop rate was bad on this one). I pacify split the mobs, and used stuns to keep aggro. I had the druid root the mobs so I could back up and heal. Everyone dotted once I had aggro. <br /> <br />We won the adventure with 15 minutes to spare. <br /> <br />Would I start a level 65 adventure with a cleric tanking? not typically (maybe if hes better equipped than me). However, the lack of tank didn't prevent us from winning. Remember, using the same stuns that pallies get (and some they don't), a cleric can hold aggro pretty well, and tank better than just about any equally equipped caster or priest. <br /> <br />But my other comment still holds to the second poster in this thread. A cleric should NEVER let someone die, because they are busy playing tank, while there is a tank in the group. <br /> <br />[ <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Mon Aug  2 11:58:01 2004 by xaanru</span></i></p>
